(489, 'Photographer of the month interview: mr mojo risin''!!', 'Congratulations on winning the second ever photographer of the month. Hopefully you guys enjoy the interview!\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTell us a little bit about yourself.\r\n\r\nI''m Danny Pasminski, just turned 18 and finished highschool. I went to a catholic high school all four years. It sucked, and so did most of the people there, with a few exceptions of close friends I made. I''m now going to a community college, with an undeclared major, and hopefully am going to transfer to a university within a year or two.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nHow old were you when you first got into photography? What got you interested?\r\n\r\nI started skateboarding about 7 years ago, and have always been interested documenting our exploits and shenanigans. You know, typical early teenage bullshit. Around sophomore year, skateboarding, filming, and taking photos started to get more serious... but serious doesn''t seem like the right word. We started taking the train down to the city a lot more and meeting new people. Eventually we started going on week long skate trips to other states and stuff. Thats when I wanted to start taking photos more. Just traveling to different cities and having fun with your friends. Thats what its all about.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWere there any key photographers or influences that really played a part in the work you do now?\r\n\r\nIve always loved looking through skateboard magazines, and skate books. Not any photographer in particular, but I get psyched on "behind the scenes" photos relating to skateboarding. Those images that you can immediately connect with cause you''ve been in that situation before.\r\n\r\nWhat kept you going for so long?\r\n\r\nUmm, I guess skateboarding and traveling. Also, just trying to be spontaneous. Doing the same thing everyday kills me. If you try to stay open to things and explore, it''s like photos oportunities present themselves to you. You just have to keep your eyes open and keep trying to look at things from multiple perspectives. That might sound cliche, but it really seems to be true.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nHave you ever thought of selling some of your work?\r\n\r\nShit, if anyone wanted to buy a print or something, I would be so psyched. I''d probably let them name the price too, as long as it covered the cost of paper and developer. haha\r\n\r\nIn ten years, where do you see yourself? personally and photography wise. Where do you want to be?\r\n\r\nI just want to be still taking pictures. I dont expect to be making a career out of it, even though I would love to. Hopefully I am still skateboarding. They both feed my love for each other.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat''s your set up? Any new gear coming your way soon?\r\n\r\nAs of right now, I mostly shoot film. I have a Nikon FE, and a couple little point and shoots for 35mm. Oh, and I recently got a cannonet for free, but the meter is fried. I also just got a bronica SQ with birthday money. Dont really see any new gear in the short future. I would rather be simplistic and light weight, than have a lot of gear that sits in a studio.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nspeaking of gear, what''s your go to set up?\r\n\r\nProbably my bronica or my FE. If Im going to a party, or show, I''ll bring my one touch or some sort of point and shoot.\r\n\r\nWhat''s your preferred photography style?\r\n\r\nStreet photography, or candids. I really enjoy taking pictures of things the way they are. You know, in their natural habitat. It just seems so much more true. Taking studio portraits doesnt even seem fun at all.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat''s your favorite thing about taking pictures?\r\n\r\nGeez, I dont even know where to start. The documentation process is awesome. Your taking a fraction of a second of an event, and slowing it down to the point where you can just stare at it for however long you like. I love that you can take that one moment, and put your creative spin on it, and have other people see and experience what you''ve just seen. Its almost like your making the moment real. Kinda like, "pics or it never happened"\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTo wrap up the interview, if you could change one thing about photography as a whole, what would it be?\r\n\r\nNothing really, to be honest. I like how everything is.\r\n\r\nIf I did have to choose though it would probably the redundancy of it. Theres just so many photos that look the same. People dump hundreds and hundreds of photos into an facebook album with very minute differences. Its like, maybe none of them really matter anyways.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n-for titles and more of mojo''s pictures, head on over to his flickr page\r\nhttp://www.flickr.com/people/dannypasminski/', 418, 1, '2012-08-31 07:30:00'),
