(568, 'Bones, Ricta, and Spitfire (Review)', 'Bones Wheels, Ricta Wheels, and Spitfire wheels are among the most popular and controversial wheels to be used by our modern skateboarding community. At this point, I''ve tried all three brands and some different formulas.\r\n\r\nMy first set of wheels were Bones STFs. They were the V3 shape, I believe, and were/are slim and slippery on most terrains. They still haven''t worn down too much (I''m pretty sure that they began as 51 or 52 millimeters; now, they''re about 48s after months of heavy powersliding and reverts). No flatspots occurred, but they did cone out just a bit. I popped a couple of bearings in them, but not many. HOWEVER, the Bones 100s (formula, not wheel thickness), did get slight flatspots, but they slid right out after a couple minutes of rolling around. Those wore down and coned out much quicker, as they were softer. They felt like a good medium, though, so I ended up getting another pair.\r\n\r\nI''m skating Rictas right now -- the Nyjah 50mm Chrome Cores -- and they are a dream. They''re a boxy shape for locking into grinds better, slide twice as well, and wear down VERY slowly. In addition, the cores protect bearings from popping and make the wheels spin straighter and faster. There isn''t much else to say; they''re great wheels.\r\n\r\nSpitfires, unlike Bones and Rictas, are known to be very grippy. I own a pair, now, and although the wheels are F1 Streetburners that were made to slide, they do grip quite a bit, to the point where boardslides are near impossible on unwaxed park concrete. Just as well, I skated them for about two weeks until I noticed that my board kept slowing down immensely after pushing. I checked the wheels and two or three of my bearings popped but stayed inside the wheels. The experience was made worse when I couldn''t get them out -- just like when I was setting the wheels up and the bearings would refuse to go into the wheel unless forced in by screwing the nuts on.\r\n\r\nOverall, Spitfires are overplayed, in my opinion, and Bones and Ricta seem to make superior wheels for street skating. Perhaps it''s different for transition and vert, but I don''t skate those enough to know.\r\n\r\nAny thoughts or comments on your favorite or least favorite wheels would be awesome to hear!', 2017, 0, '2014-03-17 13:00:00'),
