(295, 'Those are longboards. The Santa Cruz-ers are all china-made, but the trucks are good and the boards look great. The wheels are the shortfall, but they''re not BAD, just not as good as the "real stuff". America still makes the best wheels, and it''s in large, soft wheelage where the tech and design advantages are seen most. So, when the time comes, you buck up for some gringo wheels and then that thing will be even better... more than decent boards to start with though and if you''re stoked by it -- get it!', 406, 184, 0, '2011-06-28 07:30:00'),
(296, 'yea im debating wheteher or not to get a cruiser or a sector 9 longboard', 406, 215, 1, '2011-06-28 07:30:00'),
(297, 'I just bought the Santa Cruz Street Cruzer, the black with the big skull on it. I ditched the bearings right away. They are supposed to be ABEC 7 but I had a brand new set of Bones Redz that I put in and they were faster and spun longer. The wheels are pretty soft and I will probably ditch those in a little while. But it''s something that''s actually pretty good for the money and just change out a piece or two and figure out what you want to do. Wheels will probably be next for me, then maybe some new trucks and eventually a new deck and then I''ll build this one back up and have a speed board and a carving board. Who knows.', 406, 212, 0, '2011-06-28 07:30:00'),
(298, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Ethan\nhttp://www.thelongboardstore.com/lon...able-complete/\r\nhttp://www.thelongboardstore.com/lon...hine-complete/\r\n\r\nso i''ve been looking at getting a longboard lately, specifically one that would be good at sliding and i come''d down to getting one of the 2 completes above. so which ones do you guys think i should get? and im open to other recommendations also.\r\nI''ve never heard of the first brand, and it seems pretty sketchy. For the Time Mathewhine, that''s a pretty poor setup. With 50* trucks, it''s going to be really overwedged. TLS sells some shitty gear/completes. You''re better off with stores like longboardskater, muirskate, east coast core skates, pretty noise lab, motion boardshop, or stoked skateboards.\r\n\r\nFor a sliding board, do you want topmount, dropthrough, or drop deck? A couple brands to look into are Earthwing, Rayne, Jati, Comet, Jet, and Tutone. An awesome sliding setup would be an Earthwing Supermodel with Indy 215''s and something like 81a Abec 11 Freerides/Flashbacks, Cult Classics, Metro Motions, Venom Sidewinders, Venom Tweakers, Nersh Smoothies, etc.', 406, 186, 1, '2011-06-28 07:30:00'),
(299, 'I''d definitely recommend an Earthwing Supermodel. Durable, cheap and with a great shape/sexy concave. Also, completes are never a good idea.', 406, 183, 0, '2011-06-28 07:30:00'),
