INSERT INTO `responses` (`id`, `content`, `postid`, `userid`, `havemedia`, `response_timestamp`) VALUES
(1252, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Rev J\r\nOnly you can answer that. I''m about 5''9", 150 lbs, and have size 8 shoes. In 6 months back on a board I came to the conclusion that I wanted a smaller deck, different wheels and bearings than I was riding. Here are videos of my 2 favorite skaters:\r\nhttp://m.youtube.com/watch?v=xBvGzObIZsQ\r\n\r\nhttp://m.youtube.com/watch?v=cbSbbY5ibas\r\n\r\nI slowly realized as I was progressing I realized that I had to change a couple of things in my set up to make what I was trying for easier. This is way too heavy a conversation to get into with a beginner. Lets just say taste and preferences are fluid and subjective.\r\nI mean, he stated he wants to skate around fast, not freestyle so I''m sure an avg deck size is going to be fine.\r\n\r\n\r\n@Antipop - I liked your post and I think you''re on the right track. 8" should feel pretty good, if you''re building a second setup like it sounds like you are you could try an 8.5 with 149''s and 54/55mm wheels. If going fast and skating around is what is appealing that would be a good size. 8"/139 with 52mm would be a great size for skating park/street, flip tricks and grinds etc. Trying both would certainly help you figure out what you like if money isn''t a big issue.\r\n\r\nI''m a bit mixed on safety gear myself, I''ve never felt the need although a helmet would be a good idea, knee pads probably won''t do anything as you don''t hit your knees much skating, wrist guards can both help or hurt more... do you tend to sprain joints or break bones? If you break bones maybe don''t wear them... Elbow pads and shin guards might save you some pain though and there are no risks with either of those.\r\n\r\nAnyways good luck man.', 434, 277, 0, '2013-10-31 07:30:00'),
(1253, 'Actually Casual, Kilian Martin rides an 8". I was just giving him the advice that as he progresses that his preferences are going to change.', 434, 466, 0, '2013-10-31 07:30:00'),
(1254, 'I read that Real, Krooked, Anti-Hero, Venture, Thunder, Spitfire and DLXSF are all made by Deluxe Distribution-\r\n\r\nWould that mean that Krooked decks, Anti-Hero decks, Real decks, etc are all the same? Seems like I can''t go wrong as long as I go with a deck made by Deluxe Distribution. Let me know what you think. I appreciate every response that I''ve got. Every post is helpful.', 434, 477, 0, '2013-10-31 07:30:00'),
(1255, 'That is true but the shapes differ. I''m a big fan of Real decks but there are many good brands. I''ve had Real decks that lasted me months and I''ve also broken them within one hour... you just never know, land on any board wrong and it could snap. Anyways best thing is just go to a shop and stand on a few boards, Real, Krooked, Baker, Blanks, whatever man just step on some boards and see what you like under your feet, that''s probably more important than brand. That being said... I love Real, the shapes always felt right to me.', 434, 277, 0, '2013-10-31 07:30:00'),
(1256, 'Wait. I found a sicker deck- I found a Real deck that I love. It''s 8.02. Should I stick with 54mm wheels or should I get 55mm?', 434, 477, 0, '2013-10-31 07:30:00'),
(1257, 'I think 54 is good, it''s preference though I don''t wanna steer you wrong although 2mm isn''t a big dif (like from 52).. Since you''re hyped on Deluxe I''m going to suggest Spitfire Formula Fours. Classic 99, 54mm. I have Bones STF''s right now (52) and honestly as fun as they are to slide on they aren''t that smooth, plasticy feeling... Theres a thread on the F4''s somewhere here and everybody loves them. I say 99 not 101 because I don''t think a new rider needs hard ass wheels that slide out too easy.\r\n\r\nEdit - BTW I think once you get over 55mm you kinda get into "big wheel territory". Some people love that but a lot hate it, it''s above avg so that says something. Great for cruising but could make flip tricks harder etc... That''s why people are saying 52-54, it''s just the best range for street on avg.', 434, 277, 0, '2013-10-31 07:30:00'),
