(1278, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Rory\nDo you think it would be dumb to be impulsive and get two completes at the same time?\r\nIf you''ve got the cash why not... But you might as well work out what size and shape board you like before buying more than one of them. Buy a single board and see how you like it, if you don''t absolutely love it then maybe try another one, then you''ll have the other one to fall pack on.\r\n\r\nIf you have the money then why not... It''s unnecessary, but why not!', 434, 222, 1, '2013-11-02 07:30:00'),
(1279, 'Double post!!\r\n\r\nQuote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Quincy\nIt could go both ways- 1 could be a vert board, 1 could be a street board, or they could be similar.\r\nThis is the main reason you should think about having 2 boards.\r\nI see a lot of skaters at my park riding bowls and transition, and their boards are suitably shaped (IE, shaped like this) and they really are a more suitable board than my standard popsicle shape.\r\n\r\nIt really does make a difference, but while you''re only just getting into skating you may as well use one board for everything.', 434, 222, 1, '2013-11-02 07:30:00'),
(1280, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Guillermo\nIt could go both ways- 1 could be a vert board, 1 could be a street board, or they could be similar.\r\nI would say get a tranny/bowl/cruiser board with indys and big wheels (risers IMO) and a street board with smaller wheels and stuff. If anything, you can get a friend to skating and let him use one of your boards too.', 434, 267, 1, '2013-11-02 07:30:00'),
