(2186, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Rylee\nThis thread is concerning the subjects and threads asking which deck brand is "better", or which has more "flip".\r\n\r\n\r\nYou aren''t going to find the answers to these questions on a messageboard or from any of your friends, the deck that you''ll find to be the best will come from your personal experiences with them. Sometimes it''ll take months before you find a board that will truly work for you. Just try different brands and designs. And don''t be affraid to try a brand you aren''t familiar with. And don''t stick to buying only one brand through out your life unless you know it''s one that truly works for you. Don''t ever buy a deck just for the name and logo. Also don''t be affraid to ask questions to the sales dude at your skateshop, they know alot more than you think and would be glad to help you out with this subject considering how most kids buy decks just out of brand interest.\r\n\r\nIt''s completly fine to ask question in this forum about it, but just keep what I said in mind.\r\nYeah I just started skating a few months ago and started out with a crap board until I could afford a good deck, so I started looking online at the skateshops sites and looked at what I liked and asked many questions to people that know alot more about skating then I do. I was going to buy an element, but a friend of mine told me that if Im going to skate street dont buy element cuzz he did and regreted it and theyre easy to snap. He suggested enjoi, and I love enjoi now I have the panda rasta deck and its amazing. Everyone I have talked to about enjoi has something good to say about it, and I ride other decks all the time that my friends get so I can get a good feel of what other brands have to offer. I say that you dont look dumb for asking questions you look dumb when trying to look like you know everything and end up knowing nothing for not taking the time to research, ask questions and build up your own oppinion on sertain brands.', 495, 719, 0, '2007-10-14 18:30:00'),
