(3320, 'Lakai Mariano -\r\n\r\nStyle: The look of this shoe is definitely a strong point. No matter which, of the few color ways you buy, you shall not be disappointed. Its built with suede and leather, giving a classic and stylish look to it.\r\n\r\nComfort: When you first slip your foot in, whether it be trying it on or what not, you feel a lot of pressure at the arch in your foot. Needless to say, the arch is high in this shoe. But, after about one day or less of wearing the shoe, your arch molds to the arch, which is a great thing for your foot! After the arch attack goes away, this shoe could be one of the most comfortable shoes on the market today! The thin material the shoe is made of allows your foot to become one with the shoe.\r\n\r\nBoardfeel: The part of a shoe that most people are always looking for most is boardfeel. And the Mariano brings that to the table. The sole is very thin, and so is the sole pad, allowing for great board feel! However, basically the only downside of this shoe, the great boardfeel takes away a lot from the padding. Even after landing a five stair, I could feel the sting on the bottom of my foot. The shoe does have an EVA mid-sole, but it does not do as much good as it should.\r\n\r\nGrip: The grip was pretty average. I mean, it was good, but could have been better, especially around the toe area. The shoe uses the zig-zig pattern, in line with a circle pattern. I would have been much happier with the grip if it was all zigzags, because that held up well, and the circles did not. This all happened in about one month. Which is still pretty good.\r\n\r\nDurability: Although the shoe is thin, it has superb durability. After finally getting the shoe, I skated for about one and half to two hours, doing kickflips, heelflip, varial flips, varial heelflips, every trick I knew, not a scratch. After that I was quite happy with the shoe, and looked forward to wearing it. The toe cap was what I was impressed with the most, I skated constantly doing a variety of flip tricks every single day for about 3 months, still, the mariano was perfectly skate-able(with very minor rips. Then, after my 3rd month, it started to tear in the toe cap, and on the sole. The hidden lace protection system actually works! I didnt have to change my laces the entire four months I had them!\r\n\r\nOverall: Overall the Lakai Mariano was a great shoe for me! Obviously, the results will differ from person to person, but there most likely will not be any drastic changes. The price was a hefty $75, but it was definitely worth it! So, if youre looking for a very durable, thin, and stylish shoe, I would give my highest recommendations to the Mariano.', 517, 370, 0, '2007-01-06 18:30:00'),
