(3434, 'There is really no use for this review thread because most of the people who review shoes report that their shoes lasted longer than a month. All skate shoe companies use 400 nbs rubber, which is very grippy, but wears down quickly depending on the shape of the tread: ie zig-zag, waffle, etc. Larger athletic shoe companies such as nike, adidas, and reebok use a harder and less grippy rubber that lasts longer. Soles on skate shoes should be completely burned out after 2-3 weeks of heavy skating. Soles on nikes and adidas''s can last 3-4 weeks tops. Uppers are generally similar and if the shoes are not vulcanized, they will rip usually after the first few days of skating them. Cushioning is generally the same in most skate shoes with eva inserts, but soletech, dc, supra, and adidas have gel and air inserts that are generally ineffective in protecting against heel bruises. Nike has rather effective cushioning in most of their skate shoes with dual density foam insoles that implement zoom air technology. Vulcanized shoes usually have better board feel and grip than non-vulcanized, but it depends on the sole thickness and the type of rubber. I have skated all brands of skate shoes and when it comes to buying shoes, its all about preference. Keep in mind that this is coming from someone who is not shop sponsored and who skates their shoes to the death, so if you skate harder than me, your shoes will wear out faster, and if you are still new to skateboarding your shoes will probably last a few months regardless of the brand.', 517, 1155, 0, '2007-12-09 18:30:00'),
