(3576, 'I haven''t been skating for very long, so I have only had two pairs of new shoes, but here you go:\r\n\r\nCirca Combat Cero Lo''s: Lightweight, solid toe so no ripping, good grip, good feel, fairly durable, lasted me 3-4 months, 4.5/5\r\n\r\nLakai Koston Select Lo''s: yeah, got them on sale for labor day, they''re old, so what?\r\nFairly durable, but not really much grip or board feel. they look nice..., 2/5', 517, 1480, 0, '2010-04-12 18:30:00'),
(3577, 'Thought I might try to get this thread back to life.\r\n\r\nAdidas Superskate- Durable as hell, it has a huge toecap with suede that seems unrippble. The grip is the regular Adidas grip, not too grippy, but lasts. I had the mids and the collar and tongue were heavily padded, they hug your ankle. One thing I hated was the super thin insole. Shit isn''t comforable at all, no arch support, but gives you great boardfeel if you''re in to that.\r\n\r\nEmerica Francis- They are very comfortable at first. I had the mids again and they are more durable than I thought. The grip is pretty much all gone where it counts, but thre aren''t holes in the bottom yet. The toecap has formed a hole, but it only goes though 2 layers of the shoe and hasn''t hit the third layer yet. The STI level 0 (I checked on the STI website, that''s what it actually is) is prety good at first, but it flattens out over time and has no arch support being a completely flat insole. The laces haven''t ripped yet, but are somewhat fraying, and with the help of some shoegoo, this shoe could have a pretty long life.', 517, 374, 0, '2010-07-18 18:30:00'),
(3578, 'Lakai Biebel 2- Lasted a long time, good impact support, good grip, nice boardfeel and were comfy 8/10\r\nEtnies RVM- Didn''t last long, bad impact support, very comfy and excellent boardfeel 7/10\r\nLakai Telford- Lasted ages, great impact support, long time to break in and good grip 9/10', 517, 796, 0, '2010-12-29 18:30:00'),
