(3614, 'Emerica Francis: Decent shoe with good ankle support, durability, and style. The soles were average as with most Emerica shoes lasting about 4 months of moderate skating.\r\nDC Command: These were actually my first skate shoes I got at some Quicksilver store along with a mini cruiser board. The soles are the greatest feature on this shoe-- they last forever. The stitching starts to tear after about a week of skating though, so shoe goo is a must. The shoe is very bulky however, which may be a turn off to many. I still use the same pairs from 2008 as work shoes.\r\nFallen Rival SL: This is another bulky shoe, but it skates well. It will protect your feet undoubtedly.\r\nEmerica Reynolds 3: These were my last pair of shoes. Overall, it''s a very balanced shoe. There''s significant boardfeel as well as protection. The soles last only for a few months so shoe goo may prove useful; especially to the "kickflip area"\r\nAdidas Adi-Ease: These were the most uncomfortable shoes I''ve ever skated, because they run narrow and my feet are somewhat wider. It will squeeze the bottom of my foot whenever I''m pushing around and cause it to feel like it''s on fire. I don''t recommend these to those with wider feet. I feel like I can ollie higher in them though.\r\nNike 6.0 Mogan Mids: I don''t think these are even skate shoes, but I guess I''ll review them anyway. They are very comfortable and stylish shoes with the velcro and colorways. The soles are good quality as well. I feel as if it doesn''t grip well to the board though, and the front of the shoe will tear very easily.\r\nNike Ruckus LR I copped these shoes on a clearance rack at some random store at a shopping outlet. They are pretty thin lows that are comparable to the classic Vans. The soles are different than anything I''ve seen before. It''s almost a plastic-y type of deal that sacrifices grip for durability. It has substantial grip though and if you superglue/shoe goo the front before you skate it, it will never wear out. Pretty chill shoe', 517, 1499, 0, '2013-06-12 18:30:00'),
(3615, 'Last 6 Shoes Ive Skated\r\n\r\nSome Converse from Target: They weren''t very good, although the grip lasted long and the toecap was triple stitched, if i skated them hard they would be done in 2 weeks. 6/10\r\n\r\nC1RCA 205: Actually really good and incredibly durable. Skated them for 3.5 months and there was only a small hole on the side. They were very grippy and had incredible boardfeel, although maybe too much boardfeel because i would get bruises after 10 minutes on a 4 stair. Yep a 4 stair. but overall they were very durable and very nice 9/10\r\n\r\nShaun White Fremont: Good Impact support, good, thick insoles, terrible boardfeel bad quality suede, good price, Bad quality canvas, plastic like outsole. 3/10\r\n\r\nConverse Rune Glifberg pro model: I dont think its actually been officially released to the public yet but they were sick. They had amazing breathability, skated em for two months no hole, but i did have shoe goo. The grip blew quickly and the sole and foxing tape seperated pretty quickly. They had good flick and the impact support was pretty good never got a heel bruise in em but i only skated like 6 stairs. I had these for two months and liked em 8/10\r\n\r\nDC Tonik S: Hated em bad boardfeel, bad impact support, felt cheaply made, ripped laces quickly and not durable at all!! 4/10\r\n\r\nCurrent: Dvs Daewon 12''er: Got em cheap, they were on sale when the Daewon 13 CT''s came out so i got em for $50. With shoe goo, holy crap they are nice and the best shoes ive ever skated. Yes the insoles sucked, just replace em and they also have the heelbruise support technology, these have amazing amazing impact, boardfeel and flick. They dont really rip laces and have amazing quality suede and the grip is lasting long. I would definatly rate these a 10/10', 517, 266, 0, '2013-06-13 18:30:00'),
