(10980, 'I ride loose and been riding a pair of the 5.85 V3s since December and love them.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPro Tip:\r\n\r\nRemove the top washer if you ride loose. It''s the only way until the bushings break in. If you don''t remove it there is no way to get them loose enough to feel good without the kingpin nut falling off ;)', 541, 445, 0, '2014-02-25 18:30:00'),
(10981, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nI ride loose and been riding a pair of the 5.85 V3s since December and love them.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPro Tip:\r\n\r\nRemove the top washer if you ride loose. It''s the only way until the bushings break in. If you don''t remove it there is no way to get them loose enough to feel good without the kingpin nut falling off ;)\r\nThanks for the tip but I think that''s where I''m confused. Aren''t Bones bushings supposed to be broken in from the start? I didnt have to break them in on my Indy''s or Thunders', 541, 263, 0, '2014-02-26 18:30:00'),
(10982, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by BMCsteve\r\nAren''t Bones bushings supposed to be broken in from the start?\r\nTo an extent, they are not magically set to your desired level of being broken in. I was riding an 2 year old set of bones mediums (which really means they are super soft now) in a pair of ACEs AND I ride loose. Switching to the NEW theeves with NEW pivot cups and bushings, I felt like you did, and was going ot use my old bushings until I remembered to take off the top washer. Then everything was right as rain: They were loose and felt ''broken in out of the box''.\r\n\r\nQuote:\r\nOriginally Posted by BMCsteve\r\nI didnt have to break them in on my Indy''s or Thunders\r\nYes, you did, you just don''t remember it ;)\r\n\r\nJust take off the top washer, that''s all there is to it. Small price to pay for such an amazing truck (and once you break them in, add the washer back on).', 541, 445, 0, '2014-02-26 18:30:00'),
(10983, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nTo an extent, they are not magically set to your desired level of being broken in. I was riding an 2 year old set of bones mediums (which really means they are super soft now) in a pair of ACEs AND I ride loose. Switching to the NEW theeves with NEW pivot cups and bushings, I felt like you did, and was going ot use my old bushings until I remembered to take off the top washer. Then everything was right as rain: They were loose and felt ''broken in out of the box''.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nYes, you did, you just don''t remember it ;)\r\n\r\nJust take off the top washer, that''s all there is to it. Small price to pay for such an amazing truck (and once you break them in, add the washer back on).\r\nAlright. I''m going to give them a fair shot. Thanks for the tips and advice. I really want to warm up to Theeve because I planned on buying the new TiH when they are released this summer', 541, 263, 0, '2014-02-26 18:30:00'),
(10984, 'I did two things that seem to have helped so far. I swapped out the kingpin nuts with Indy ones. The plastic lock part on the threads starts lower in the nut so you dont have to put them on as tight. I also used some armorall on the bushings and pivot cups which not only quiets them but helps them break in a bit faster.\r\n\r\nso far so good', 541, 263, 0, '2014-02-26 18:30:00'),
