(10988, 'Alright, I spent an hour and a half garage skating (still raining in NorCal) and I''m happy to admit that I was completely wrong about these trucks.\r\n\r\nI took the top washer off and literally spent 10-15 minutes rocking the board side to side while taking a break every couple minutes to tighten them up. After 15 minutes I put the top washer back on, snugged them down and there a whole new animal.\r\n\r\nI got so used to my Indy''s that I think I was mistaking the Theeve''s stability for a lack of turning. They just feel completely different than Indy''s which maybe I didn''t expect.\r\n\r\nI don''t have a setup in my garage so I was just skating flat ground. I landed everything cleaner. My pop was also noticeably higher. I don''t attribute that to them being a few grams lighter but rather to the stability factory.\r\n\r\nAll in all I jumped to conclusions way too quickly on these. I can''t wait to take them to the park/streets hopefully this weekend. I''ll report back after some more riding and once I get some grinding laid down\r\n\r\nThanks again to Martha for the help. Totally worth the trouble', 541, 263, 0, '2014-02-26 18:30:00'),
(10989, 'Would love to see this turned into a proper full on review, i really like Theeve as a company but am yet to try a pair of their trucks.', 541, 222, 0, '2014-02-27 18:30:00'),
(10990, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Vivica\r\nWould love to see this turned into a proper full on review, i really like Theeve as a company but am yet to try a pair of their trucks.\r\nI''m going to keep this going for the next few months (until the TiH V2 come out). Once I get out to the park I''ll post some updates and pics regarding the grinding on metal coping and concrete and I''m curious to see how they turn in bowls', 541, 263, 0, '2014-02-27 18:30:00'),
(10991, 'Cool man, if you have time to write out decent reviews you should consider being a content writer for SBC.', 541, 222, 0, '2014-02-27 18:30:00'),
(10992, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by BMCsteve\r\nI got so used to my Indy''s that I think I was mistaking the Theeve''s stability for a lack of turning. They just feel completely different than Indy''s which maybe I didn''t expect.\r\nTheeve have the stability of Thunders (and trucks like it) when centered with a quick snap back to center AND the ability to turn deep like Indy and ACEs without feeling wobbly) and no wheel bite. People like what they like and won''t try new shit (doesn''t help that theeve are expensive (even though the cost difference is the price of bones bushings...) and caught a bad rap last go around due to the bushing blowout issue (which never affected me as I ride loose and don''t crank the shit out of my bushings).\r\n\r\nI''ve said it before, they''ve taken the best of other trucks and combined them into one truck.\r\n\r\nQuote:\r\nOriginally Posted by BMCsteve\r\n\r\nThanks again to Martha for the help. Totally worth the trouble\r\nNo worries, I was glad to help. Just wait until those trucks/bushings break in some more...=)\r\n\r\nQuote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nBones Hard broken in = Fresh Bones Mediums\r\n\r\nBones Mediums broken in = Fresh Bones Softs, correct?\r\nYes, Broken in hards = fresh mediums, if only it didn''t take so damn long to break in the hards...\r\n\r\nNo, fresh softs =/= broken in mediums. The softs are wickedly soft unless your under 100lbs or so imo. Case in point: My ~60lb daughters had issues with meds set to medium so I swapped out for softs; set to the same looseness, I had to tighten the up for them.\r\n\r\nBones Hard Bushings = 96A\r\nFive points of duro difference\r\nBones Medium Bushings = 91A\r\nTen points of duro difference\r\nBones Soft Bushings = 81A', 541, 445, 0, '2014-02-28 18:30:00'),
(10993, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nTheeve have the stability of Thunders (and trucks like it) when centered with a quick snap back to center AND the ability to turn deep like Indy and ACEs without feeling wobbly) and no wheel bite. People like what they like and won''t try new shit (doesn''t help that theeve are expensive (even though the cost difference is the price of bones bushings...) and caught a bad rap last go around due to the bushing blowout issue (which never affected me as I ride loose and don''t crank the shit out of my bushings).\r\n\r\nI''ve said it before, they''ve taken the best of other trucks and combined them into one truck.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNo worries, I was glad to help. Just wait until those trucks/bushings break in some more...=)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nYes, Broken in hards = fresh mediums, if only it didn''t take so damn long to break in the hards...\r\n\r\nNo, fresh softs =/= broken in mediums. The softs are wickedly soft unless your under 100lbs or so imo. Case in point: My ~60lb daughters had issues with meds set to medium so I swapped out for softs; set to the same looseness, I had to tighten the up for them.\r\n\r\nBones Hard Bushings = 96A\r\nFive points of duro difference\r\nBones Medium Bushings = 91A\r\nTen points of duro difference\r\nBones Soft Bushings = 81A\r\nAre these your favourite trucks currently?', 541, 580, 0, '2014-03-01 18:30:00'),
