(11086, 'Was finally able to unbox my theeves this morning! The TiKings are VERY light compared to my old 139 forged foil indys from two years ago but not CRAZY light compared to my ACE 44s and Thunder IIs 147s (yeah I know that''s a lot of trucks).\r\n\r\nThe kingpin appears inline with the ACE''s, lower and not near the hanger like the Thunders''\r\n\r\nCasting was a bit of a letdown, not that it matters but compared to the Thunders they were just as janky with rough edges and nicks/marks all over them. Compared to the ACE''s tho..man the ACE''s are just fantastic to look at, so smooth, no jagged anything, really svelte and sleek looking; they look like a quality product whereas the Theeves and Thunders look like Wallmart trucks when put against the ACEs.\r\n\r\nI''ll get to test them out tomorrow morning at the park.', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-14 18:30:00'),
(11087, 'can''t wait.....so they''re lighter than your Indy''s but not your Thunder''s and Ace''s? I love my Indy''s, they''re so awesome I don''t know. I ride Krux too and I can immediately tell a difference when I jump onto another set of trucks. I was looking into some Theeve''s or Thunder''s. The TiKing''s are the best or the middle of the line truck?', 549, 794, 0, '2011-09-15 18:30:00'),
(11088, 'For sure lighter than the Indy''s, with the thunder IIs 8" and the ACEs it was pretty close (8 vs 8.25), the thunder II baseplate has much less material/hollowed out so size and hollows considered they might be on par? But I could tell with the ACEs, them being heavier but not OMFG THEY''RE FEATHERS kind of thing ;)\r\n\r\nAll that said, the ''new'' Thunder II geometry doesn''t feel all that ''new'' sure they turn ok, with that twitchy thunder feel still and Indy''s are Indy''s. Now the ACES and Theeves have a distinct feeling to them compared to the Thunder/Indy style, the ACEs turn, really turn, when you want them, very responsive and smooth. I rode the theeves today and I was killing it at the park (didn''t even bother looseing or tightening, just rolled out), but compared to the ACES, in the bowl, the aces were a bit more carvey, but that might be to them being broken in bushing wise.\r\n\r\nThe TiKings are second to the top:\r\n\r\nTiH - Theeve''s One Piece Axleless Ti-Hanger is up to twice as strong and 20% lighter than anything on the market. Titanium is up to 8 times harder than aluminum alloy, lending them exceptional longevity. Being constructed from one single piece of titanium, with no separate axle rod, it can never, ever get axle slip. These trucks were the inspiration behind the now famous true-turning geometry that all Theeve trucks share and come standard with Bones Hardcore Bushings.\r\n\r\nTiKing - The TiKING model features the world''s first hollow titanium kingpin. Forged from 6/4 aerospace grade titanium, it is 55% lighter than a regular steel kingpin. The trucks also feature the same 6/4 titanium axles as used on our TiAX trucks, come standard with Bones Hardcore Bushings and share the same true-turn geometry of the rest of the Theeve range.\r\n\r\nTiAX - Theeve has created the worlds first 6/4 Titanium axle truck. TiAX Titanium axles are 40% lighter and 2 times stronger than standard steel axles. This gives you a weight saving and less chance of bending axles. Titanium / alloy blend with non-slip 6/4 Aerospace grade Titanium axles, Grade 8 king pins and Bones Hardcore Bushings standard.\r\n\r\nCsx - Theeves take on a classic truck with a twist. Titanium / alloy blend with non-slip cro-moly steel axles, grade 8 king pins and Bones Hardcore Bushings standard.\r\n\r\nIt feels to me that TiH are a tranny lovers perfect truck; I wanted to try them but they are too cost prohibitive for me. TiKings are just TIAX with a hollow kingping.\r\n\r\nHonestly if can''t go wrong with Thunders but after riding ACE and Theeve and feeling a very different style of turning than the rest, I couldn''t go back. I hope the theeves live up to the ACEs I''ve already experienced.', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-15 18:30:00'),
(11089, 'ive had theeves and theyre pretty good. but theyre not for those people who love loose trucks. they do have a better turing turning geometry then independent and they feel more stable. There is a ALOT of space between the hanger and the kingpin so you can grind these down for days. i cant even imagine how long theyll last. definetly worth trying out but if your someone that likes pretty loose trucks then go with indys.', 549, 2000, 0, '2011-09-15 18:30:00'),
(11090, 'I ride loose trucks, not wobbly loose but medium loose? Just enough to turn...right now the Theeves feel a bit stiff but they''re brand new (no break in of the medium bones that come stock) so we''ll see. I''ll give''em two weeks like I did with my ACEs and see what happens; the ACEs turn really well but always feel loose, even cranked down with broken in medium bones.', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-15 18:30:00'),
(11091, 'yah theyre still amazing trucks. worse that could happen is u just have to tighten ur trucks a bit. im just trying to warn those who like theyre trucks really loose to just get something like indys instead', 549, 2000, 0, '2011-09-16 18:30:00'),
(11092, 'I have the TIH''s and they are AMAZING and SO light. a little weird at first with grinding on coping but now they grind great. and they are perfect for there turning i ride REALLY loose and they are just so great.', 549, 1477, 0, '2011-09-16 18:30:00'),
(11093, 'Bryguy, are you mainly tranny or park? I was seriously considering the TiH as I''m really only skating park right now.', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-17 18:30:00'),
(11094, 'Wasn''t feeling them today. It''s as if they didn''t want to turn at all and I''ve no room left to loosen them further without fear of the nut falling off.\r\n\r\nI had an especially hard time in the bowl, instead of being able to carve I had to lift my front truck off the wall causing me to lose all my speed and on flat I felt rigid; really weird as the other day I was killing it/they felt great.\r\n\r\nHere''s hoping it''s just today as I was almost tempted to swap''em out for my ACEs...', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-18 18:30:00'),
(11095, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nBryguy, are you mainly tranny or park? I was seriously considering the TiH as I''m really only skating park right now.\r\n\r\ni have been skating that lately yeah, they are really good at park after you break them in, but at first they seem to be really sticky. and on normal concrete ledges they are good.', 549, 1477, 0, '2011-09-18 18:30:00'),
(11096, 'Wasn''t feeling them again today so I swapped out the bones mediums with bones softs and they were instantly better...except for the fact that in less than a few hours the theeves started to demolish the bushings; one of the top blue caps is starting to separate and they are deformed as shit and I ride LOOSE!\r\n\r\nI guess I will sell them off and go back to my 8" ACEs.', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-20 18:30:00'),
(11097, 'Get khiro bushings nigga', 549, 214, 0, '2011-09-24 18:30:00'),
(11098, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by BUDOKAI\r\nGet khiro bushings nigga\r\nBeen tempted, I just don''t know where to begin with those as they''ve got 1238674512984z1253 different combinations!\r\n\r\nSuggestions?', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-24 18:30:00'),
(11099, 'I rode the TiKings a few days ago, had a good skate day overall. After the session I checked my bushings, the top rear bushing had started to crack horizontally in the middle...and I ride loose trucks, the nut is only flush with the kingpin (how they send them out stock).\r\n\r\nI''ve ordered some Khiro Reds (med/soft) and blues (soft) with the aluminium tops but in the time being I switched back to my ace 33s and what I noticed was:\r\n\r\nThe ACEs just rock in the pool, carving is so nice with them compared to the theeves, which won''t turn in a corner like the ACEs, I feel so much more fluid poolskating with the ACEs; both do just fine on street/mini with the Aces being ''turnier'' I know, nice word but that''s the best I can .\r\n\r\nThe Theeves feel like Indy''s or thunder''s to me but a bit smoother, stable, decent turn but nothing spectacular. Which I find funny as many used to compare them to ACEs due to the look.\r\n\r\nI''m really hoping the khiros get them rocking.', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-28 18:30:00'),
(11100, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nBeen tempted, I just don''t know where to begin with those as they''ve got 1238674512984z1253 different combinations!\r\n\r\nSuggestions?\r\nshort double cones with built in washer. Yellow?\r\nif it''s too short just put little washers on the bottom.', 549, 2001, 0, '2011-09-28 18:30:00'),
(11101, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Overkrook\r\nshort double cones with built in washer. Yellow?\r\nif it''s too short just put little washers on the bottom.\r\nI went with two sets of aluminium inserts reds and blues with the idea that I will mix and match: hard bottoms and soft tops.', 549, 445, 0, '2011-09-28 18:30:00'),
(11102, 'Sold them =D\r\n\r\nPutting the Khiros in my ACEs (33s and 44s).', 549, 445, 0, '2011-10-04 18:30:00'),
(11103, 'Wise choice, Khiros are the bomb.', 549, 364, 0, '2011-10-04 18:30:00'),
(11104, 'Nice choice.', 549, 214, 0, '2011-10-04 18:30:00'),
(11105, 'I recently setup a board with 8.6" Theeve TiKings and they felt pretty high so I compared them to my Thunder HIs and what do you know, the Thunders HIs are lower (same height as ACE LOs) with the Theeves as high as my ACE HIs, intersting as Theeve tag these as ''mid trucks''.\r\n\r\nSo, ACE HIs are as high as Theeve ''mids'' and both are taller than Thunder HIs which are as low as ACE LOs...\r\n\r\nSilly industry measurements!\r\n\r\nAnyway, after swapping out broken-in pivot cups & broken-in bones bushings into the Theeves, I''ve determined that they really don''t turn :P especially if you like them slightly loose to very loose...', 549, 445, 0, '2012-02-05 18:30:00'),
(11106, 'Oh, I forgot to add that the 149 Thunder Hollow Lights felt lighter both in hand (to three different people w/eyes closed) and on the same setup.', 549, 445, 0, '2012-02-05 18:30:00'),
(11107, 'theeves are the best end of story', 549, 232, 0, '2012-02-05 18:30:00'),
(11108, 'I went to the khiro site and the make a 6.785 deck. it''s supposed to be for kids but i want one to fuck around on', 549, 2002, 0, '2012-02-11 18:30:00'),
(11109, 'Good to know! That Khiro deck is just what I''ve been looking for for my kiddos, either that or the Grindking/Termite decks as I won''t touch the darkstar/blind completes that size.', 549, 445, 0, '2012-02-14 18:30:00'),
(11110, 'HOLY SHIT!', 549, 2003, 0, '2012-02-25 18:30:00'),
(11111, 'Holy shit what the fuck hahaha! Is that yours? That''s the worst thing I''ve ever seen happen to a truck. That''s fucking horrible. And I thought Venture''s baseplates were bad.', 549, 504, 0, '2012-02-25 18:30:00'),
(11112, 'Looks like a bad temper, complete lack of temper after quenching. Properly tempered steel shouldn''t break off jagged like that, it should have at least stretched or deformed along that cleavage before it broke. I''d send that back to Theeve for warranty replacement. Obviously defective.', 549, 1080, 0, '2012-02-25 18:30:00'),
(11113, 'It took about a 2 weeks for my theeve ti-ax trucks with bones medium bushings to be perfect and it was fucking worth the wait. I had to tighten them about 3 times (just a little everytime) as the bushings broke in. I skate concrete ledges fairly often and these thing wear down really slow compared to my ventures. They also grind just as well if not better than my ventures. Also, the photo above is from the first batch of theeve trucks and are known to be defective. They have since changed the hangar design. So if you find theeve trucks for a steal, they are more than likely those ones from the first batch.', 549, 2004, 0, '2012-02-27 18:30:00'),
(11114, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Shannon\nAlso, the photo above is from the first batch of theeve trucks and are known to be defective. They have since changed the hangar design. So if you find theeve trucks for a steal, they are more than likely those ones from the first batch.\r\n\r\ncreaturefi3nd is correct, the V1 Theeves looked (and apparently felt) more like ACEs do:', 549, 445, 0, '2012-02-28 18:30:00'),
(11115, 'Well done Brootal - looks like a good skate session ;)', 549, 815, 0, '2012-04-05 18:30:00'),
(11116, 'Hey Martha,\r\n\r\nWhat is the axel length of your Ace 44s? I''m currently riding some Ace 33s (8") on a 8.25" deck, and I''m wondering if Ace 44s would stick out from under the 8.25" decks that I ride, or if it would be a better fit and ride.. Also, I mostly ride street, but sometimes I skate mini and bowls.. I''m not sure if I should stick with the 33s or go for some 44s next time.', 549, 2005, 0, '2012-04-06 18:30:00'),
(11117, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Shannon\nHey Martha,\r\n\r\nWhat is the axel length of your Ace 44s? I''m currently riding some Ace 33s (8") on a 8.25" deck, and I''m wondering if Ace 44s would stick out from under the 8.25" decks that I ride, or if it would be a better fit and ride.. Also, I mostly ride street, but sometimes I skate mini and bowls.. I''m not sure if I should stick with the 33s or go for some 44s next time.\r\nI can help you out, too ;)\r\nACE 44 got 8.25" (axle to axle) ... perfect for 8.25" - 8.75" - so fits perfect under 8.25" ...\r\nI would say 8" works also good for 8.25" Decks... when you grind ''em down / or got some extra money - you can go to ACE 44 (if you stay with 8.25" or bigger decks)... you''ll be more stable with these trucks (while landing tricks - drop-in bowl - etc.).\r\n\r\nCheers,', 549, 815, 0, '2012-04-09 18:30:00'),
(11118, 'Found some Theeve CSXs for about 20 bucks each, about five dollars less than the other Theeves on the website. Whats the difference between the two?\r\n\r\n\r\nAnd if anyone could help with an Indy Vs Theeve review, that''d be great.', 549, 610, 0, '2012-05-26 18:30:00'),
(11119, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Crass\r\nFound some Theeve CSXs for about 20 bucks each, about five dollars less than the other Theeves on the website. Whats the difference between the two?\r\n\r\n\r\nAnd if anyone could help with an Indy Vs Theeve review, that''d be great.\r\nTheeve review (incl. the bushing problem about buldge and/ or blow out) at:\r\nhttp://oldmanskater.blogspot.de/2011...ew-part-5.html\r\n\r\n-> on CSX, TiAX and hollow TiAX, old TiH (all V2)\r\n\r\nOnly TiAX Low and CSX Low and new TiH won''t have that problem.\r\n\r\n\r\ndifference: CSX = "normal" Truck... TiAX = titanium axles (=less weight)', 549, 815, 0, '2012-05-26 18:30:00'),
(11120, 'INTERNETS!1\r\n\r\nCSX - Titanium / alloy blend with non-slip cro-moly steel axles, grade 8 king pins\r\n\r\nTiAX - Titanium / alloy blend with non-slip 6/4 Aerospace grade Titanium axles, Grade 8 king pins\r\n\r\nTiKing - The TiKING model features the world''s first hollow titanium kingpin. Forged from 6/4 aerospace grade titanium, it is 55% lighter than a regular steel kingpin. The trucks also feature the same 6/4 titanium axles as used on our TiAX trucks\r\n\r\nTiH - Theeve''s One Piece Axleless Ti-Hanger is up to twice as strong and 20% lighter than anything on the market. Titanium is up to 8 times harder than aluminum alloy, lending them exceptional longevity. Being constructed from one single piece of titanium, with no separate axle rod, it can never, ever get axle slip.\r\n\r\nI''ve only recently ridden Indy''s again and you know I''ve ridden Theeves in the past (still riding a pair on one of my setups) - they are very similar, probably the closest in feel to each other than any other pairing of trucks (they''ve been called the modern indy); that said, I will give the edge to the Indy 159s I have (compared to the the TiKings) when it comes to carving in pools.', 549, 445, 0, '2012-05-28 18:30:00'),
(11121, 'Allright thanks guys. I just ordered some Indy 149s. Might pick up some bones bushings later if i get the money. Thanks for the help!', 549, 610, 0, '2012-05-28 18:30:00'),
(11122, 'Did you get the new 149s? That are based off the old geometry like the 159s?', 549, 445, 0, '2012-05-28 18:30:00'),
(11123, 'http://www.skatewarehouse.com/Indepe....html?color=SI\r\n\r\n\r\nThese, I''m not sure to be honest. Just looked good.', 549, 610, 0, '2012-05-29 18:30:00'),
(11124, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Crass\r\nAllright thanks guys. I just ordered some Indy 149s. Might pick up some bones bushings later if i get the money. Thanks for the help!\r\nyou can''t be wrong with them - good choice.\r\nYou must try them later with bones hc bushings (91a)... also try to experimental with bottom and without bottom cupwasher. You''ll luv the combination of Indys + Bones :)\r\n\r\nHave fun!', 549, 815, 0, '2012-05-29 18:30:00'),
(11125, 'Just so helpful info. If you have bushing problems with theeves, swapping out the pivot cups for khiro small hard pivot cups does solve the problem (you also have to take out the bottom washer). I''m a heavier guy, but still like turn-ability. I replaced my pivot cups, took off my bottom washer, put a replaced the top bones medium bushing with bones hard bushings, and replaced the top washers with small diameter washers(so they don''t dig into the hangar). I skate them with the nut flush with the king pin. Now they skate like a dream, even better than when I first broke them in.', 549, 2004, 0, '2012-06-09 18:30:00'),
(11126, 'So you ditched the Indy''s?\r\n\r\nI''ve just started riding my TiKings again (smaller board) with the small (usually top) washer on the bottom - they came with both a large washer on the bottom and small washer on top - and no top washer in order to A) maintain stock geometry and B) be able to keep the nut flush/secure while still being loose and not having to crank it down thereby exposing the top threads of the kinpin.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI''m actually starting to like them more than my ACEs (on street/mixed terrain) but wish I had them in 8.25" again (8" right now) and I have had zero bushing problems.\r\n\r\n51mm wheels and loose hi (same height as my HI aces) trucks = wheel burn baby!', 549, 445, 0, '2012-06-09 18:30:00'),
(11127, 'I was never riding Indy''s lol. I''ve been riding my TiAxes since january. There was like a 3 week period where the they were riding like complete shit and the bushings would bulge and pop out every 40 minutes. I had the pivot cups and replacement bushings for like a week during that time, but I''m lazy and don''t like doing anything to my setup until I go to replace my deck(I have some hollow titanium kingpins waiting to be put in). When I took them apart the bushings had been completely destroyed in the center. Here''s what they look like now though. They actually turn even smoother with the khiro pivot cups. I never though about swapping out the bushings like you did though. I''ve got the mids(really his) with 52 mm wheels. As you can see I got some pretty deep weel burns. I want to just swap out the medium bottom bushings for the hard one''s but breaking them in is gonna suuuck...they are so damn stiff and I like to turn\r\n\r\n\r\nHere''s the smaller washer. You can see where the old one was digging into the hangar', 549, 2004, 0, '2012-06-12 18:30:00'),
(11128, 'oh man.. local skateshop got some Theeve TiAX 5.85 for 50% off (17 US Dollar / each)...\r\n\r\nI think I''ll give em (again) a try with some khiro pivot cups...\r\nWe''ll see what happens...', 549, 815, 0, '2012-08-09 18:30:00'),
(11129, 'That''s a hell of a deal! Just make sure they are V2s =D\r\n\r\nI still have my TiKings on my smaller setup! Great trucks...I''ve noticed that they really do grind very well, compared to my thunders, especially on crappy l/edges, they grind much faster with less effort (and fewer sticks).', 549, 605, 0, '2012-08-09 18:30:00'),
(11130, 'review after 1st 5h session: Theeve TiAX 5.85 with Khiro pivot small hard:\r\n\r\nToday I took the 1st ride with ''em:\r\nat first.. it really felt uncomfortable to ride with the really hard khiro pivot cups (small)... I locker the kingpin nut a lot.. so the kingpin top is really lower than the top of the kingpin nut -but I still don''t grind on the kingpin nut. I took 30 min - hard turns in bowl/ pool to get the pivot cups comfortable...\r\n\r\nAh btw, what I notice was.. that I had really hard to stick the pivots in their place and hat to push (a little bit) the hanger into the pivot cup (so the kingpin ins centered in the hanger-hole.\r\n\r\nAfter the first rides the Theeve felt damn comfortable... they ain''t that turny like Thunder with bones hc bushings BUT they are really stable and you can do every trick very clean... I think (maybe it was just luck) with ''em I got the best run today - cause I focus on grind tricks (metal-coping) and Theeve are really really comfortable and fast about grinds.\r\n\r\nAfter an 5h session - I take a look at the bushings (don''t use a bottom washer - just top)... and they seems to be (1st look) fine... I could recordnize that they starts to deform yet... It seems that if you loose your kingpin nut a lot more - than they bushings won''t be stressed to much...\r\n\r\nBut this is just my first Impression... I found my perfect setting @ kingpin nut and don''t want to loose the nut again to see what''s up with the bushings...\r\n\r\nAh yeah.. also I noticed that I didn''t get any wheelburns.. no marks on my brand new creature deck... back in the days I got notice able burn marks with the Theeve TiaX V2 on my deck with 58mm wheels and 1/4" riser pad... now (with khiro pivot) I use the same riser pad size but use 60mm wheels and no burns...\r\n\r\nWe''ll see what happens to the bushings if I took more sessions with them...', 549, 815, 0, '2012-08-10 18:30:00'),
(11131, 'update:\r\nWell, I added to the khiro pivot cup some Independent red bushings (some guys tried that)... but I don''t know... it ain''t the same than with bones hc bushings. I had to ride them really loose... on drop-in in, from 50-50, makes grind, I scratch on the kingpin nut. The thing with the Independent reds seems to work for and there ain''t bushings probs but I rode a long time bones hc bushings and it''s very uncomfortable when the trucks ain''t getting back to center (with indy red bushings).', 549, 815, 0, '2012-08-17 18:30:00'),
(11132, 'Were you having bad bushing problems on the theeves? I only ask as your above post mentions you might have seen them start to deform?', 549, 605, 0, '2012-08-18 18:30:00'),
(11133, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by 13sinisterurge13\r\nWere you having bad bushing problems on the theeves? I only ask as your above post mentions you might have seen them start to deform?\r\nAfter 2 session.. the back bottom bushing (bones hc bushings - stock) starts to deform - it starts to rise over the lip... when I removed the bones hc bushings - I notice that it seems that the soft-core starts to sperate from the hard-core... Also I ride ''em loose.. so the axle nut is really loose on the kingpin and you could see a mark of the bones bushings (hard core) on the baseplate (where the kingpin sits).\r\n\r\nSo I switch to Indys red bushings to test ''em -but they didn''t felt right.\r\n\r\nBtw I just could get some hard pivot cups (small) of khiro.. I noticed that it scratch the pivot of the hanger that sits in the pivot-cup... don''t know if it''s right or could kill the pivot of the hanger.\r\n\r\nAll in all... my Theeve time is over for now - not a bad truck, but after some trys - I didn''t get use too ;]', 549, 815, 0, '2012-08-18 18:30:00'),
(11134, 'I''m trying a new set of the Reynolds Indys as of today =D', 549, 605, 0, '2012-08-18 18:30:00'),
(11135, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Shannon\nI''m trying a new set of the Reynolds Indys as of today =D\r\nordered today a pair of Independent 149 Stage 10 (w. bones hc bushings) - ride ''em till the new ones with old Independent geometry comes out\r\n\r\nAfter a lot of testing different trucks - for me - there is only a choice between Thunders and Indys', 549, 815, 0, '2012-08-18 18:30:00'),
(11136, 'I was getting too much wheel bite on my thunder Hollow Light HIs, not burn but BITE, I was getting pitched off my board.\r\n\r\nFeels like Thunders are to be ridden tighter to take advantage of their twitchy/sporty turn compared to indys which I think lend themselves to be ridden better loose by comparison.', 549, 605, 0, '2012-08-18 18:30:00'),
(11137, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Shannon\nI was getting too much wheel bite on my thunder Hollow Light HIs, not burn but BITE, I was getting pitched off my board.\r\n\r\nFeels like Thunders are to be ridden tighter to take advantage of their twitchy/sporty turn compared to indys which I think lend themselves to be ridden better loose by comparison.\r\nyeah the Hollow/ Lights Hi are, with their honeycomb baseplate, really low (compage to normal Thunders Hi). I always got wheelburns with Thunders... much deeper than Independent Trucks. I am not sure but I think also deeper than Ace trucks. But getting on speed and with some bones spf (hard wheels) that ain''t a problem with 1/4" riser and 60mm wheels. I rode my Thunders always as loose as I could.\r\n-but for sure, Thunders make good trucks... I can''t say that I like Indys or Thunders more... both are perfect (for me) :)', 549, 815, 0, '2012-08-19 18:30:00'),
(11138, 'So after ditching the 149 thunder hollow lights, I went to a pair of the new 149 Indy Reynolds (as I noted above) w/bones mediums. They''re a bit taller, which I wanted and not as twitchy and I rode the a little tighter. I still got bite, just not as bad.\r\n\r\nThat said, I am going back to Theeves! Say what you want about weight but man those thunders are stupid light and the Indy''s are not. Does it make a difference in performance? Perhaps to some, but no to me. However, I liked the way the board felt when it was lighter, with the Indy''s it just felt clunkier.\r\n\r\nSince I had the Theeves kicking around (was riding 8.18s TiKings forgot I had 8.5" TiAx hangers) I put the TiAx hangers on the Tiking plates and off to the races. Taller truck than Thunders, turn better and are light than Indy (and not sticky).\r\n\r\nNow if I can just find a wheel I love I''ll be set!', 549, 605, 0, '2012-09-11 18:30:00'),
(11139, 'Been riding my Theeves for two months now and notices something really odd with the pivot cups area on the baseplate and was curious if anyone else had seen this.\r\n\r\nThe pivot cups fit snugly on the hanger pivot but when in the baseplate, the hanger pivot/pivot cup both move around the pivot cup cavity which isn''t normal. It is as if the pivot cup recess in the baseplate has gotten larger over time. It gives them a very twitchy sort of feel, very different than when they were new.\r\n\r\nI notice that Khiro sells ''large'' pivot cups, perhaps they would fill in the slack?', 549, 445, 0, '2012-10-15 18:30:00'),
(11140, 'not on my own but I rode some of these kinds of problems on the Facebook Users-Comments on the official Theeve-Channel. Also found some comments like this on the web... also some people comments that this problem also exist the the mounting holes of the baseplate... maybe it''s an material problem of the baseplate?', 549, 815, 0, '2012-10-15 18:30:00'),
(11141, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by chris44141\r\nnot on my own but I rode some of these kinds of problems on the Facebook Users-Comments on the official Theeve-Channel. Also found some comments like this on the web... also some people comments that this problem also exist the the mounting holes of the baseplate... maybe it''s an material problem of the baseplate?\r\nUnsure but I know when I got them everything was snug in the cup cavity, I''ve been running Khiro softs in them for a while and I know when I put them in it was a snug fit, now, not hard, soft, doh doh or the theeve STOCK cups fit in either baseplate snugly, yet any cup I have on hand fits snug in my 159s (Khiro softs) or ACE44s (khiro hards).', 549, 445, 0, '2012-10-15 18:30:00'),
(11142, 'Thread Necromancy.\r\n\r\nSome new info on the the V3s! With the Agenda show happening really soon, some info is getting out there.\r\n\r\nAgenda info: http://agenda.transworld.net/2012/11...-co-at-agenda/\r\n\r\nNew Catalog: http://issuu.com/theevetrucks/docs/t...cks_summer2013\r\n\r\nTruck blog that covers Theeve (and others).\r\nhttp://skateboardingismylifetimespor...ming-soon.html\r\n\r\nObviously the team is riding them already: http://www.skateboardermag.com/featu...ordan-hoffart/\r\n\r\nPiecing it all together it appears that the bushing bulge is fixed (I never got this as I ride loose trucks) with a new bushing seat (as seen on the new tiking los), two new sizes have been added, they''re lighter (?), revised yoke design and the TiH is gone and the one piece axle/hanger design brought to all models.\r\n\r\nTiKing one piece so slip Ti axle and hollow pins\r\nTiAX same no slip Ti axle with standard pins\r\nCSX steel no-slip axle, standard pins <-- interesting twist\r\n\r\nStill come stock with Bones Bushings. No word on geometry changes.\r\n\r\nLooking forward to being able to afford a pair of TiKings :P', 549, 445, 0, '2013-07-08 18:30:00'),
(11143, 'best is the headline on "issuu" page ->\r\n"probably about to piss everyone off again!!!""\r\n\r\nI''m excited if Theeve piss everyone off again', 549, 815, 0, '2013-07-09 18:30:00'),
(11144, 'Great tagline, and #hashtag ;)\r\n\r\nIf they worked out all the kinks and can get the price down (hoping they don''t jack up the TiKings to the old TiH price) they might actually gain some ground; they could also use some bigger (and better) team riders.', 549, 445, 0, '2013-07-09 18:30:00'),
