INSERT INTO `responses` (`id`, `content`, `postid`, `userid`, `havemedia`, `response_timestamp`) VALUES
(11162, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Regina\r\nI totally agree, the old street corner distrubution bushings were complete shit until broken in. Bushings in these new ventures from deluxe are pretty awsome, I prefer them to bones bushings without a doubt, they feel more stable and you can still ride them loose enough to get a turn on. I rode my mates magenta and it felt awsome, sadly there like 110 bucks in aus so I wont be getting one any time soon.\r\n\r\nI hate how people are to arrogant to give venture a try, I think they are sex after these thunder lows Ima go back to ventures no doubt\r\nI love ventures and have only skated Venture trucks for years and years now. Every improvement they''ve made over the years has made sense and they got it right the first time. The bushings in their new trucks...they got it right. Finally! I don''t get why people are so hesitant about trying their trucks either. I''m going to catch some shit for this, but Independent has been geared more and more towards the tranny, park and pool crowd for years. Thunders seem to be a good middle ground for people who skate everything and Venture has always been a truck geared towards street skaters. Park, pool and tranny skating are big right now. Street skating, not so much.', 551, 1091, 0, '2014-02-24 18:30:00'),
(11163, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nJust because you like a distribution will not mean you''re going to like every company under them.\r\nThunder, Venture and Indy are all manufactured by Ermico Enterprises, Inc. in the city of San Francisco.\r\n\r\nVenture was originally part of Streetcorner Distribution, no idea who owns the brand.\r\n\r\nIt also doesn''t mean they are designed by the same people.\r\n\r\nQuote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Midwest_Mike\r\nI love ventures and have only skated Venture trucks for years and years now. Every improvement they''ve made over the years has made sense and they got it right the first time. The bushings in their new trucks...they got it right. Finally! I don''t get why people are so hesitant about trying their trucks either. I''m going to catch some shit for this, but Independent has been geared more and more towards the tranny, park and pool crowd for years. Thunders seem to be a good middle ground for people who skate everything and Venture has always been a truck geared towards street skaters. Park, pool and tranny skating are big right now...street skating seems to be on the decline.\r\nI agree to a point, I''d say Thunder, just as much as Venture, has targeted the street crowd exclusively. When was the last time you saw a ''vert'' ad for Thunder? I mean, sure they added the Miller''s and there is Perelson but the rest are all street.\r\n\r\nPool/Park + wider boards resurgence is a good thing =D', 551, 445, 0, '2014-02-24 18:30:00'),
(11164, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nThunder, Venture and Indy are all manufactured by Ermico Enterprises, Inc. in the city of San Fransisco\r\nThanks for the info Martha! The more you know', 551, 259, 0, '2014-02-24 18:30:00'),
(11165, 'Quote:\r\nOriginally Posted by Martha\r\nThunder, Venture and Indy are all manufactured by Ermico Enterprises, Inc. in the city of San Francisco.\r\n\r\nVenture was originally part of Streetcorner Distribution, no idea who owns the brand.\r\n\r\nIt also doesn''t mean they are designed by the same people.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI agree to a point, I''d say Thunder, just as much as Venture, has targeted the street crowd exclusively. When was the last time you saw a ''vert'' ad for Thunder? I mean, sure they added the Miller''s and there is Perelson but the rest are all street.\r\n\r\nPool/Park + wider boards resurgence is a good thing =D\r\nI agree....less dicks and irritating little shits in the streets is a great thing!', 551, 1091, 0, '2014-02-24 18:30:00'),
