(11500, 'Naturals are a solid urethane pour.\r\n\r\nCored wheels have a plastic core.', 586, 445, 0, '2013-12-26 18:30:00'),
(11501, 'I just wanted to add Decomposed Keith Renna signature wheels to Martha''s list. They honestly feel better than the Bones STF I was riding before.', 586, 466, 0, '2013-12-26 18:30:00'),
(11502, 'The cores in some cored wheels are just plastic, such as nylon, and this sucks.\r\n\r\nHowever, the "good" wheelhouses use cores that are actually a very hard, injection molded urethane and become chemically bonded to the wheel urethane after the hot goo is poured into the mold with the waiting core. These cores give you a stable bearing seat, the ability to use spacers the way the Z-Boys and bearing mfgr''s (the makers, not the branders) intended you to for fast wheels and cannot separate from the rest of the wheel.\r\n\r\nRicta -brand is made in one of those wheelhouses (actually, the best of them) and gives a good example of bonded urethane cores.', 586, 184, 0, '2014-01-09 18:30:00'),
(11503, '54-55 is about as big as you''ll want to go with Indys and no risers.', 587, 474, 0, '2013-11-18 18:30:00'),
